Couples often remain in unhappy relationships because of guilt, shame, the desire to avoid the cost and pain of marital litigation, or the practical ramifications divorce might have on their children. Divorce can also be extremely difficult from a practical standpoint, considering problems related to finances, custody, property division, and insurance issues. There are no easy solutions in a divorce. However, litigation is almost never the best choice.

One alternative is an uncontested divorce, where both parties are in agreement on all issues relevant to their divorce. Both spouses have decided it is time for the marriage to end, and so hire and agree on a single divorce lawyer. The divorce process then immediately moves to mediation, where the two lawyers and the client will discuss property division, child custody, and alimony claims. These issues are both resolved informally and formally, and the case is settled. The process is comparatively cheap and fast.

If spouses do not choose to have a divorce facilitated by a lawyer, Georgia courts still encourage couples who are separating to reach a mutually beneficial agreement. The judge can order the filing of a separation agreement that outlines the agreement between the parties regarding property division, alimony, child custody and child support. Working out these issues at an early point and filing an agreement to be signed by both parties removes the cost, expense and time involvement of court.
